What You Are Building
You are building MELD (Manifold-Equivalent Learning with Deployment guarantees) — a class-incremental learning framework that solves the following problem:

Retraining machine learning models from scratch every time new data arrives is computationally expensive and inefficient. While incremental learning methods exist, they often introduce bias or drift without formal guarantees. MELD is a delta-only training framework where a model can be updated using only newly arrived data, yet remain equivalent to a model retrained on the full dataset. It includes mechanisms to detect distribution shifts, correct bias introduced by recent data, and quantify equivalence with theoretical bounds. It demonstrates significant compute savings without sacrificing accuracy, calibration, or robustness.


The Core Problem MELD Solves
Every existing incremental learning framework has at least one of these fatal flaws:
Flaw 1 — They use old data (replay)
iCaRL, DER, GEM, Avalanche — all store old samples and mix them in during training. This violates the delta-only constraint, creates data privacy issues, and doesn't scale as tasks grow.
Flaw 2 — They have no pre-training safety check
EWC, SI, MAS — regularization-based methods that protect important weights. But they find out how much they forgot after training. There is no mechanism to say "this update is mathematically unsafe, don't run it."
Flaw 3 — They freeze the backbone
FeTrIL, GACL, RAD — analytic/fixed-representation methods that provide formal guarantees but only for the classifier head. The backbone is frozen after the first task and never adapts. This breaks on data with distribution shift.
Flaw 4 — They are algorithms, not frameworks
Every paper ships a method. Nobody built pluggable infrastructure. You cannot swap components. You cannot extend them. They are scripts dressed up as systems.
Flaw 5 — They have no deployment layer
None of them answer the real production question: "Is this update safe enough to ship?" They produce accuracy numbers. They don't make decisions.

How MELD Solves Every Single One
Solving Flaw 1 — Zero Old Data, Zero Replay
MELD eliminates replay entirely. Instead of storing raw data, after every task it stores a mathematical fingerprint of what the model learned:
Per class c:
  μ_c   = mean embedding vector     (where the class lives in feature space)
  Σ_c   = diagonal covariance       (how spread out the class is)
  r_c   = classifier weight norm    (for bias correction)

Global:
  F_diag = diagonal Fisher Information Matrix
           (which weights matter most to preserve)
This is called a TaskSnapshot. It captures the geometry of the model's knowledge — not the data that produced it. During the next update, MELD uses these statistics to constrain training mathematically. No images. No labels. No replay buffer.
The loss function during delta update is:
L = CrossEntropy(new_data)
  + λ₁ × KL(N(μ_c, Σ_c) || N(μ̃_c, Σ̃_c))   [geometry preservation]
  + λ₂ × Σᵢ Fᵢ × (θᵢ - θᵢ*)²               [weight protection]
Term 2 forces the embedding space for old classes to maintain the same shape. Term 3 prevents important weights from moving. Together they replace what replay does — but using only stored math, not stored data.

Solving Flaw 2 — Pre-Training Safety Oracle
This is MELD's most unique contribution. Before a single gradient step is taken, MELD computes a spectral bound on the maximum possible equivalence gap:
ε_max = λ_max(F_diag) × η × √(T × d)

where:
  λ_max(F_diag) = largest Fisher eigenvalue
                  (how sensitive the model output is to weight changes)
  η             = learning rate
  T             = number of planned gradient steps
  d             = embedding dimension
What this means:

Fisher eigenvalue measures how much model output changes per unit of weight change
Learning rate × steps estimates how far weights will move
Their product gives the worst-case accuracy drift — mathematically, before training

Decision:

If ε_max ≤ tolerance → proceed to training, the update is provably safe
If ε_max > tolerance → skip training entirely, recommend full retrain immediately

No other framework stops before wasting compute. MELD does. This is the safety oracle.
After training completes, MELD also verifies the bound held empirically — closing the loop between the promise and the reality.

Solving Flaw 3 — Full Model Updates (Backbone + Classifier)
Unlike FeTrIL or GACL which freeze the backbone after task 1, MELD updates both backbone and classifier during every task. The backbone is kept adaptive through the geometry loss — it is allowed to change as long as the change doesn't distort the old class manifolds beyond tolerance.
This means MELD handles distribution shift. If new data comes from a shifted distribution, the backbone can adapt. The geometry penalty ensures old classes are not forgotten in the process.

Solving Flaw 4 — A Real Pluggable Framework
MELD defines six abstract interfaces. Every component is swappable:
