The Complete Problem Map & How MELD Solves Everything

PROBLEM 1 — Catastrophic Forgetting
What It Is
When learning something new, artificial neural networks tend to quickly and drastically forget what they had learned before — a phenomenon known as catastrophic forgetting. GitHub
The root cause: the main cause of catastrophic forgetting seems to be overlap in the representations at the hidden layer of distributed neural networks. In a distributed representation, each input tends to create changes in the weights of many nodes — when many of the weights where "knowledge is stored" are changed, it is unlikely for prior knowledge to be kept intact. GitHub
How Others Tried to Solve It
Replay (iCaRL, GEM, DER):
Store a buffer of old samples, mix them into training on new data. Works empirically but violates the delta-only constraint, has data privacy issues, and doesn't scale — the buffer grows with every task.
EWC (Elastic Weight Consolidation):
Constrains important parameters to stay close to their old values by computing how important weights are for previous tasks using the Fisher Information Matrix. OpenReview No old data needed — but it finds out how much it forgot after training. And the quadratic regularization loss in EWC easily leads to gradient explosion when balancing old and new classes. GitHub
Knowledge Distillation (LwF):
Use the old model as a teacher — soft targets preserve old class outputs. But requires a forward pass through the teacher network on every batch, and breaks badly when new data distribution is far from old.
How MELD Solves It
MELD eliminates forgetting through geometry preservation — not data replay, not weight penalties alone. After every task it captures the full geometric fingerprint of what the model learned:
Per class c:
  μ_c  = mean embedding  (where the class lives in feature space)
  Σ_c  = covariance      (how the class is shaped)

Global:
  F_diag = diagonal Fisher Information (which weights matter)
During the next update, the loss has a geometry preservation term:
KL( N(μ_c, Σ_c) || N(μ̃_c, Σ̃_c) ) for every old class c
This directly penalizes any deformation of old class distributions in embedding space. The model is free to change weights as long as old class geometry doesn't move. This is a stronger constraint than EWC (which only looks at weight magnitude) — it looks at what the weights produce.

PROBLEM 2 — No Formal Guarantees / Blind Training
What It Is
Every existing method trains first, measures later. You run EWC or replay for 10 epochs and then check if accuracy dropped. If it did — compute wasted, model potentially broken.
Solving the continual learning problem requires more than preventing catastrophic forgetting. GitHub The field has spent 10 years improving accuracy numbers but nobody asks: "Can I mathematically guarantee this update is safe before I run it?"
How Others Tried to Solve It
Nobody has. This gap is real and confirmed by the research. GACL provides post-hoc guarantees for the classifier only. PAC-style bounds exist in theory but are never derived from the actual model geometry before training.
How MELD Solves It — The Pre-Training Safety Oracle
Before a single gradient step, MELD computes:
ε_max = λ_max(F_diag) × η × √(T × d)
What each term means:
λ_max(F_diag) — the largest Fisher eigenvalue. Fisher measures how sensitive model outputs are to weight changes. The largest eigenvalue is the worst-case sensitivity direction — if a weight moves in this direction, the output changes the most. This is extracted from the geometry of the current model.
η × √(T × d) — the maximum possible weight displacement over T gradient steps in d dimensions at learning rate η. This is derived from the optimization trajectory geometry.
Their product = the worst-case accuracy drift, derived mathematically.
If ε_max > tolerance:
→ Don't train. Recommend full retrain immediately. Zero compute wasted.
If ε_max ≤ tolerance:
→ Proceed. The update is provably bounded before training starts.
After training, MELD also verifies:
ε_actual = ||embeddings_before - embeddings_after||
and checks ε_actual ≤ ε_max. This closes the loop — promise vs reality, every task.
No other framework does this.

PROBLEM 3 — Recency Bias in the Classifier Head
What It Is
Recency bias refers to the tendency of an incrementally learned network to be biased towards classes in the most recently learned task. The classifier norm is larger for new classes than for previous ones, and the classifier bias favors the more recent classes. arXiv
In plain terms: after training on 5 new classes, those 5 classes have bigger weight vectors than all old classes. The model over-predicts them. Old class accuracy collapses even if the backbone didn't forget.
The mean weights in the FC layer for new classes are much larger than that of old classes. And the model predicts a larger logit for new classes than old classes. Moreover, the margin becomes bigger when there are more tasks. Proceedings of Machine Learning Research
How Others Tried to Solve It
BiC (Bias Correction): Adds a linear correction layer trained on a held-out validation split. Requires storing extra data and an extra training phase. BiC appears to over-compensate toward previous tasks. arXiv
WA (Weight Alignment): Scales the newest classifier head by a norm ratio. Simple and effective but applied only to the newest head — not per-class. Also hardcoded, not derived from stored geometry.
LUCIR: Uses cosine classifiers with normalized weights. Helps but still requires exemplars and doesn't formally bound the correction.
How MELD Solves It
After every update, MELD applies Analytic Per-Class Bias Correction using stored classifier norms from the snapshot:
γ_c = mean_norm(all old classes) / norm(class_c)
w_c ← γ_c × w_c   for every class c
Key differences from existing approaches:

Applied per class — not just to the newest head
Correction factor derived from stored geometry (r_c in the TaskSnapshot) — not from a formula or extra validation data
Zero old data needed — the norms were captured at snapshot time
Works for both old and new classes — equalizes the entire classifier head


PROBLEM 4 — Distribution Shift Goes Undetected
What It Is
When new data arrives from a shifted distribution — different lighting, different domain, different class balance — existing frameworks don't know. They just train. Accuracy might look fine on the new task while old class embeddings have completely moved.
This phenomenon occurs because deep learning models typically share a common set of parameters across all tasks. When trained on a new task, the optimization process updates parameters to minimize the loss for the new task, inadvertently overwriting information critical to earlier tasks. GitHub
The problem is worse when the new task distribution is far from old tasks — something no existing framework formally detects or responds to.
How Others Tried to Solve It
Nobody detects it at the embedding level. Most methods check task accuracy and assume that's enough. It isn't — a model can maintain accuracy on a task while its feature space has fundamentally shifted, making future updates unpredictable.
How MELD Solves It
After each update, MELD runs KL-based per-class drift detection:
For each old class c:
  drift_c = KL( N(μ_c_before, Σ_c_before) || N(μ_c_after, Σ_c_after) )

shift_score = mean(drift_c) over all old classes
shift_detected = (shift_score > threshold)
This catches three things accuracy alone misses:

Subtle embedding drift — class means moved even if classification is still correct
Distribution widening — class covariance expanded, making future tasks harder
Cross-class overlap — old classes drifting into each other's space

If shift is detected, it feeds directly into the deployment policy. A SHIFT_CRITICAL decision is issued even if the accuracy numbers look acceptable.

PROBLEM 5 — Stability-Plasticity Dilemma
What It Is
The stability-plasticity dilemma is a core challenge in continual deep learning. It refers to the trade-off between the ability of a model to retain and preserve previously learned knowledge (stability) and its ability to learn new information (plasticity). GitHub
Too much stability → the model can't learn new classes well.
Too much plasticity → the model forgets old classes.
Every existing method picks a fixed point on this tradeoff through hyperparameters. Lambda in EWC, memory size in replay. These are tuned offline and don't adapt.
How Others Tried to Solve It
EWC: Fixed lambda. If it's too high → can't learn new classes. If too low → forgets old ones.
Replay: Memory size controls the tradeoff. Larger buffer = more stability but more storage.
Progressive Neural Networks: Grow the network for each task. Infinite stability but network grows forever — not practical.
How MELD Solves It
MELD uses adaptive lambda scheduling for the geometry preservation term:
λ₁(t) = λ_max × e^(-decay × t)  during training epoch t

At the start of training: high geometry penalty → old knowledge protected
As training progresses: penalty anneals → new classes can be learned freely
The annealing rate is derived from the Fisher spectrum — tasks with high Fisher values (sensitive model) anneal slower; tasks with low Fisher values (robust model) anneal faster

This is not a fixed tradeoff — it adapts to the model's current sensitivity. The stability-plasticity balance is determined by the geometry of the model, not a tuned hyperparameter.

PROBLEM 6 — No Deployment Decision Layer
What It Is
Every existing framework — Avalanche, PyCIL, Mammoth, Delta Framework — produces accuracy numbers. None of them answer the production question:

"Is this update safe enough to actually deploy?"

In real ML systems, engineers have to manually inspect results and make judgment calls. There's no formal output that says "ship this" or "retrain first" with a mathematical reason.
How Others Tried to Solve It
Nobody has built this. It simply doesn't exist in the research literature as a first-class component.
