Fisher Information computation:

Run the model on a sample of the current task data (500-1000 samples, configurable)
For each sample, compute gradients of log-likelihood with respect to all parameters
Square and average: F_i = E[( ∂log p(y|x,θ) / ∂θ_i )²]
Store diagonal only — full Fisher is too large
Compute λ_max = max(F_diag) — the largest eigenvalue

Per-class manifold capture:

Run all current task data through the model backbone (no classifier)
Extract embedding vectors for each class
Compute μ_c = mean(embeddings_c) — class mean
Compute Σ_c = var(embeddings_c) + 1e-6 — diagonal covariance with numerical stability
Store both in the snapshot

Classifier norm capture:

For each class c, store r_c = ||w_c||₂ where w_c is the classifier weight vector for class c

Critical implementation detail:
The Fisher must be computed with the model in eval mode but with gradients enabled. Use a cross-entropy loss over a random subset of the current task data. Do not use the full dataset — it's too slow. 500 samples is sufficient for a diagonal approximation.

core/oracle.py
Implements SpectralSafetyOracle(SafetyOracle) — the pre-training bound derivation.
Pre-training bound formula:
ε_max = λ_max(F) × η × √(T × d)

where:
  λ_max(F)  = largest Fisher eigenvalue from snapshot
  η         = learning rate from train config
  T         = epochs × (dataset_size / batch_size) = total gradient steps
  d         = embedding dimension of the backbone
Derivation justification:

λ_max(F) measures worst-case output sensitivity per unit weight change
η × √(T × d) is the maximum Euclidean distance weights can travel in T steps in d dimensions
Their product bounds the maximum change in model outputs — and therefore the maximum accuracy gap vs full retrain
This is a spectral norm bound on the Jacobian of the model output with respect to weight changes

Post-training bound:

Re-extract embeddings for all seen classes after update
Compare against pre-update snapshot embeddings
ε_actual = mean over classes( ||μ_c_after - μ_c_before||₂ / ||μ_c_before||₂ )
This is the normalized actual drift — comparable to ε_max on the same scale

Return both values. The runner compares them.

core/updater.py
Implements GeometryConstrainedUpdater(ManifoldUpdater) — the core training loop.
The 3-term loss:
L_total = L_CE + λ₁(t) × L_geometry + λ₂ × L_ewc

L_CE       = CrossEntropy(logits, targets)        standard classification loss

L_geometry = Σ_c KL( N(μ_c, Σ_c) || N(μ̃_c, Σ̃_c) )
             where μ̃_c, Σ̃_c are the current model's class stats
             recomputed on a running basis during training
             This term penalizes deformation of old class distributions

L_ewc      = Σ_i F_i × (θ_i - θ_i*)²
             where F_i is Fisher diagonal from snapshot
             and θ_i* are the parameter values at snapshot time
             This term penalizes moving important weights
Adaptive lambda scheduling for L_geometry:
λ₁(t) = λ_max × exp(-decay_rate × t)

where:
  λ_max      = initial geometry penalty weight (default 1.0)
  decay_rate = λ_max_decay / total_epochs
  t          = current epoch

λ_max_decay is derived from Fisher: higher λ_max(F) → slower decay
This gives high geometry protection at the start (stability) and allows plasticity later in training.
EWC lambda λ₂:
Fixed per run. Default 0.4. This does not anneal — weight protection stays constant throughout.
Geometry loss computation detail:
Computing exact KL on running class stats every batch is expensive. Approximate it:

Every N batches (default N=50), extract a mini-batch of random samples
Compute current class means and variances on those samples
Compute KL against stored snapshot stats
Cache the result, use it for the next N batches
This reduces overhead to ~2% of training time

No old data enters this function at any point. The only inputs are new_data_loader and snapshot. The geometry constraint is enforced purely through the penalty terms.

core/corrector.py
Implements AnalyticNormCorrector(BiasCorrector) — post-update classifier bias fix.
The problem it solves:
After training on new classes, their classifier weight vectors have larger norms than old classes. The model over-predicts new classes. This must be fixed before evaluation and deployment.
The correction:
For every class c in all seen classes:
  γ_c = mean_norm_old_classes / norm_c
  w_c ← γ_c × w_c

where:
  mean_norm_old_classes = mean of r_c values from snapshot (stored at snapshot time)
  norm_c = current ||w_c||₂ of classifier weight for class c
Important detail:
Apply this to ALL classes, not just new ones. The mean norm anchor comes from the snapshot — it represents the target norm scale that produced good results on old tasks. Scaling all classes to this anchor equalizes the classifier without any old data.
Do not apply this during training. Call it once after the full training loop completes and before evaluation.

core/drift.py
Implements KLManifoldDriftDetector(DriftDetector) — distribution shift detection.
Per-class KL divergence:
For each old class c present in both snapshots:
  KL_c = KL( N(μ_c_before, Σ_c_before) || N(μ_c_after, Σ_c_after) )

Closed-form for diagonal Gaussians:
  KL = 0.5 × Σ_d [ log(σ_after_d/σ_before_d)
                   + (σ_before_d + (μ_before_d - μ_after_d)²) / σ_after_d
                   - 1 ]
Aggregate shift score:
shift_score = mean(KL_c) over all old classes
Severity classification:
shift_score ≤ threshold           → severity = "none"
threshold < score ≤ 2×threshold   → severity = "minor"
score > 2×threshold               → severity = "critical"
Default threshold: 0.3 (configurable).
Why mean and not max:
Max is too sensitive to a single outlier class. Mean gives a stable signal across the full distribution of old classes. Expose both in the DriftResult so the policy can use either.

core/policy.py
Implements FourStateDeployPolicy(DeployPolicy) — the deployment decision engine.
Four states and their exact conditions:
SAFE_DELTA:
  bound_held = (post_bound ≤ pre_bound)
  no_shift   = (drift.severity == "none")
  Condition: bound_held AND no_shift
  Action: deploy delta update
  Confidence: 1.0 - (post_bound / pre_bound) × 0.3

CAUTIOUS_DELTA:
  bound_held = (post_bound ≤ pre_bound)
  minor_shift = (drift.severity == "minor")
  Condition: bound_held AND minor_shift
  Action: deploy with monitoring flag
  Confidence: 0.6 - (drift.shift_score / (2 × threshold)) × 0.2

BOUND_VIOLATED:
  Condition: post_bound > pre_bound
  Action: full retrain
  Confidence: 1.0 (certain)

SHIFT_CRITICAL:
  Condition: drift.severity == "critical"
  Action: full retrain
  Confidence: 1.0 (certain)

Priority: BOUND_VIOLATED and SHIFT_CRITICAL override everything.
If both fire, state = BOUND_VIOLATED (bound violation is the stronger signal).
Compute savings computation:
savings_percent = ((t_full_retrain - t_delta) / t_full_retrain) × 100
Wall time is measured by the benchmarks runner and passed in.

models/backbone.py
Build ResNet family: resnet20, resnet32, resnet44, resnet56.
Each backbone exposes:

forward(x) -> embeddings — returns feature vectors, not logits
out_dim: int — embedding dimension (64 for resnet32 on CIFAR)

The backbone does NOT include the classifier head. Classifier is separate.

models/classifier.py
Implements the incremental multi-head classifier:

Starts with one linear head per task
adaption(nb_new_classes) — adds a new head for the next task
forward(embeddings) -> logits — concatenates all heads
weight_vectors(class_id) -> Tensor — returns weight vector for a specific class
all_norms() -> dict[int, float] — returns current norm for every class


benchmarks/runner.py
The end-to-end benchmark loop. This wires all components together.
For each task:

Load task data via Continuum
Adapt classifier head for new classes
If task > 0: capture snapshot via SnapshotStrategy
If task > 0: compute pre-bound via SafetyOracle.pre_bound()
If pre-bound > tolerance: record BOUND_EXCEEDED, skip training, go to step 10
Run ManifoldUpdater.update() — train on new data only
Run BiasCorrector.correct() — fix classifier head
Capture post-update snapshot
Compute post-bound via SafetyOracle.post_bound()
Run DriftDetector.detect()
Run DeployPolicy.decide()
Evaluate model — top1, top5, ECE, per-class accuracy, confusion matrix
Also run full retrain baseline on all seen data — for comparison
Write task result to results.json

Full retrain baseline:
For every task, also train a fresh model from scratch on all data seen so far. This is the gold standard. Compute savings = delta time vs full retrain time.

benchmarks/metrics.py
Compute and return:

top1_accuracy — standard top-1
top5_accuracy — standard top-5
ece — Expected Calibration Error (15 bins)
per_class_accuracy — accuracy per class
confusion_matrix — full confusion matrix
forgetting — accuracy drop on old tasks since they were first learned
backward_transfer — how much learning new tasks affected old ones
compute_savings_percent — time saved vs full retrain
equivalence_gap — cosine similarity gap between confusion matrices


