What Makes MELD Different From Everything Else
State this clearly in the README and docs:

MELD is the first framework that treats class-incremental learning as a safety verification problem. It does not ask "how do we train incrementally?" — it asks "can we mathematically guarantee this update is safe before we run it?" Every existing framework trains first and measures later. MELD derives a formal spectral bound from the model's own geometry before a single gradient step, trains on new data only using manifold-constrained optimization that replaces replay with stored mathematical statistics, corrects classifier bias analytically, verifies the bound held after training, and outputs a reasoned four-state deployment decision. Every component is a pluggable abstract interface — making MELD infrastructure that others can build on, extend, and benchmark against.


This is the complete specification. Build it exactly as described.